comment: People can really exaggerate things and victimize themselves. There are tons of questionable cases out there. The fact that someone can just make claims without proof and get people fired is ridiculous. Not to mention how people are fired over their controversial statements because corporations don't want negative representation. They're just greedily preserving their public image. It just goes to show how massive corporations don't care about the people they employ. Which is understandable with such high requirements but at the same time it seems like an opinionated extremist attempt to dismantle anything they don't approve of. It's more like a corporate dictatorship than an artistic opportunity. Then again I guess it falls in line with what it is to be a professional. It's not like anyone could destroy someone like Johnny Depp with such an immortal reputation anyways. To think that people would just disown someone over some petty accusation just shows how selfish and careless people are, especially in the entertainment industry. I'm not trying to minimize but really people are so quick to burn someone down. It's almost like they have such a perfectionist consumer mentality for the people they respect as a fan. They want everyone to do and say everything the way they want to. But what about the fact that you have real people playing these roles and human beings can make mistakes. Yet sometimes those mistakes are bloated and oversaturated with unrealistic expectations of what a person should be. Also some of these things that happen are signs that someone should be cared for and not rejected. But I guess people have zero tolerance for certain actions. Just like the ruthless corporations and production companies that rule the world. It's not enough to have everyone on their payroll, they want to control every aspect of it as well. I better stop writing here or it's going to be a five hour long segment. Opps. This got complicated.

comment:
I think regardless of how this plays out in the courts, by now so much has come to light that JD is definitely winning in the court of public opinion. And when all is said and done, that is the one that will matter most to his career and legacy. The movie companies will hire or not based on whether or not they think he will be a marketable name, and whether people believe him to be innocent even if the courts did not say so. AH (and the MS entertainment media) made a huge miscalculation in regards to how public opinion would go.
But yes, this case is important exactly because of stereotypes. Not just about DV, but about parenting in divorce cases or in anything else, where we assume too much without actually first examining the facts of each individual simply based on what we expect to be true based on the usual social roles. It allows people like AH to abuse those expectations, because they know them as well as the rest of us. We all know what is normal in society, so it is harder to prove when something goes against that.

comment: Men are many times today, victims. I just had charges for domestic abuse dropped after dealing with court for months. I can't imagine years of accusations in a court, but I can imagine years of abuse in a home. It sucks the life out of you, it literally will slowly (sometimes quickly) kill you body and soul, because "men don't get abused by women" right? I lived with and have a child with a raging alcoholic psycho, manipulative, conniving, abusive, con artist. She was and is potentially an insane addict/alcoholic. I called the police on her five times after knives had been pulled on me, I'd been assaulted, I'd had guns pulled on me and been threatened with death, agg assault, hit in the head with fists, alcohol bottles and objects, nails dug into me into the muscle/veins that bled like stab wounds, being told "I'd be taken care of" (murdered essentially), shirts torn off me and having "insurance on my life". All forms of psychological and emotional abuse imaginable... The police even documented this and THEY NEVER OFFERED TO LOCK HER UP EVEN AT HER OWN ADMITTANCE OF WHAT SHE WAS DOING! They let me leave with our some child nights this would happen. Sometimes he saw it sometimes he slept thru it. Guess what, the same lead police officer showed up on every call until the last time I called when other officers did and she was asked to  "press charges on me" that night after dragging me out of bed in our spare bedroom asleep with our 2 yearold son and hitting me over the head with the alcohol I'd hidden from her, as it exploded all over us and my sleeping son . I'm telling you, women can get away with murder until they don't. If it had been me doing any of those things even once I'd been taken to jail immediately. Women that dont even try to lie or hide it get away with murder until they finally kill you and it's over with, and some ask why didn't I leave? I did, I tried, but financial obligations and my sons safety always brought me back. I couldn't abandon him, I'd rather protect him and die or be maimed then leave him in the care of a psychotic mother using him against me or in the hands of strangers. I had no where else to turn. With the stupid plandemic crap going on all this is just worse. I haven't worked in months. Luckily I'm not going to prison and suicide isn't an option with four kids of my own. So men, if you're a "tuff guy" and this kind of crap is going on in your life, know that you're not alone. There is hope at some point, something has to give.  It's sad that the society that champions its self with "sex equality" has none at all when it comes to equal Justice in male and female relationships in many places. comment: Amber Heard should be on the hook to build a Center for men who are fleeing from domestic violence. Hollywood should back this. In my opinion the center should be called : The Hartman Center. In honor of Phil Hartman who was murdered while in an abusive marriage. Johnny Depp cuts the ribbon during the dedication with his family & Phil's. Have it built in a way that these men can bring their children with them. They deserve a safe place. They deserve legal counsel, personal counseling and financial support. We have facilities all over for women fleeing domestic violence so why not men? Sadly many are lost to suicide, drugs & alcohol once they are thrown out by their abusive partners. Johnny opened up the conversation that men too get abused. The conversation needs to be continued and the stigma that they are weak dropped. I've known men who were abused & had their lives turned upside down. Some are no longer with us choosing death over fighting for justice not given the chance to tell their side of the story. I also know men who took their children & left. Moving in with family to start over again. It's a bigger problem than most are willing to admit. We need to start a movement & help those who cannot help themselves. There should be shelters all over for men like there are for women. R.I.P. Phil Hartman üíî Justice for Johnny ‚ù§ Time to make a change.
